INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("66", "1", "2015-08-13 01:18:55", "2015-08-13 01:18:55", "When I was encouraged to write about what I know.  To write from the heart. To tell it in a way that is unique to me. To allow others to see my inner traveler, people might be encouraged to come along for the ride. When I started my experiential travel company, <a title=\"Blaycation\" href=\"http://blaycation.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Blaycation</a>, I knew i’d enjoy sharing these experiences with people, but I had no idea i’d be writing about them . Thank you, my Australian Travel Blogger friend Megan Claire for all your advice, emails and your words of encouragement.  After you read this blog, you need to check out her link below.\r\n\r\nWhen I travel, I get my artistic juices flowing. It seems like every single day there are so many mesmerizing sights that inspire me.  The gleam of a spoon, the reflection in a puddle, the rain drops on a metal table. They all make me want to paint.\r\n\r\nI am smiling just thinking about some of these moments as I write this. Like the Turkish tea cup and saucer. The one with the tiny little spoon from the back alley café in Istanbul. It’s sexy and slender little translucent  shape with its ornate hand painted design; Or the chaos and color of the shops in Bundi India. With their kaleidoscope of hanging textiles; hand made leather goods and overly friendly shop keeper Romeo. He would not let you pass without saying. “Please this is Romeo Corner, please come, have some chai tea.”; Or on my first Safari in Tsavo East, watching in awe, the majestic male lions relaxing in the Kenyan shade next to their zebra kill.\r\n\r\nSometimes I take photos of these special experiences, other times I just sit there, wonder struck by the sights, smells and sounds of what I am witnessing. These simple pleasures are what inspire me they keep me young. They make me search out new experiences, and thanks to my youngest son, Nicholas, they now get expressed via the canvas.\r\n\r\nFor me, painting makes me happy. It has given me an outlet to share these travel experiences in a new way, a highly personal way, my way! Painting has become my inner form of traveling.\r\n\r\nAs I found out, there are loads of inner travellers out there just like me. Some of them use a camera to capture the most amazing memories, others use video or their computers to write inspirational blogs;  Others write poetry or compose music and sing songs when they travel.\r\n\r\nPainting for me was discovered quite simply by accident on a Saturday afternoon. My wife Dee was out and my oldest three children, all in their mid teens, were busy with their friends. It was just me and my youngest son, Nicholas. We had taken turns playing hockeygoalie in the garage but we weren’t finished having fun.  I have a bit of a competitive streak in me, and he had just won the accuracy competition. So when I asked him what we were going to do next and he said “lets paint”it was on!\r\n\r\nWithout giving it much thought, we hopped in the car, drove to the store, bought some supplies and decided to just create.  I needed a little inspiration.  Luckily for us we had taken a whole load of pictures over the years on our family travels. I rifled through them; Nick chose a Train and I chose a picture that was very personal to me. It was a photo of my wife Dee sitting on a beach in Positano. I absolutely loved it. It showed the beach, the boats, the umbrellas the winding streets, the iconic church and the brightly colored picturesque amalfi coastal town clinging to the cliffs.\r\n\r\nI also recalled a conversation I had with my grade 4 teacher, Mrs Levy. She would say. “Painting has no rules.”  “No one can tell you your paining is wrong.”  So with my 10 year old son challenging me, my grade 4 teacher inspiring me we began to paint.\r\n\r\nI slapped a little color here, added some impressionism there and even used a chopstick in a few places instead of the paintbrush. I was thrilled by the results.  Here is my first painting.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-150 aligncenter\" src=\"http://insider.blaycation.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG_9301-300x231.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_9301\" width=\"300\" height=\"231\" />\r\n\r\nAs I look at it again, I see my inner child boxing with myself as a parent, husband and father. I love the almost finger painting quality of this picture and yet subtle detail of Dee sitting on the bottom left hand side of the painting with her camera. I remember this day so vividly and I will always have this painting. It has propelled me to further explore my inner traveler to do more paintings and inspire others too.\r\n\r\nI continued to travel,  with my eyes wide open. I visited every gallery I could, got totally inspired and painted even more. Friends would encourage me, some would even purchase my work. The canvas became my communication for expressing myself.\r\n\r\nI was not alone. When I painted, someone I would meet would sketch, another new friend would pick his guitar and another would write poetry. We all had a common theme, each story, picture, verse or painting were all inspired from something we had witnessed when we traveled.  So if you use a camera, a pen,  a guitar, your voice or a chisel,  I encourage you to continue. It is amazing what happens when you surround yourself with like minded people. You listen and you get invigorated, you learn something new.  These experiences are especially useful to me in developing <a title=\"experiential travel\" href=\"http://blaycation.com/\" target=\"_blank\">experiential travel</a> for my company.\r\n\r\nIn the past three years since I started painting I have stepped back to revisit some of my most memorable travel experiences. I have now over 100 paintings and lasting memories as a result of finding my “inner traveler.” Here are a few of my paintings, and a quick story behind their inspirations. I hope you enjoy.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-141 aligncenter\" src=\"http://insider.blaycation.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/second-236x300.jpg\" alt=\"second\" width=\"236\" height=\"300\" />\r\n\r\nI spent over fifteen days on a mopped driving through Northern Thailand with my two new French friends chasing hidden waterfalls, organic coffee, thai cuisineand other cultural experiences. Those two weeks were so much fun that I returned the following year for more. This painting, of our little Chaing Mai courtyard became not only a perfect gathering place for daily travelers to interact and have a drink or a Thai bar-b-q but also became my painting sanctuary for almost a week. I call this one my Thai courtyard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-140 aligncenter\" src=\"http://insider.blaycation.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/rome-234x300.jpg\" alt=\"rome\" width=\"234\" height=\"300\" />\r\n\r\nIn Rome, the coliseum was iconic. I pictured this view being the same for over 2000 years. I imagined the gladiators inside, the crowd cheering and the powerful symbol it represents even to this day.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-136 aligncenter\" src=\"http://insider.blaycation.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/cuba-230x300.jpg\" alt=\"cuba\" width=\"230\" height=\"300\" />\r\n\r\nIn Cuba I was struck by the smiles, the salsa and the cigars. This painting represents the late night rum infused drinks, the musical talent and excitement as well as the genuine happiness the Cuban people. The Cigar box is a metaphor for the people and the Island of Cuba  with it’s multicultural  mixture of people. The Cigar burning represents the dictatorship that will eventually be distinguished.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-138 aligncenter\" src=\"http://insider.blaycation.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/paris-241x300.jpg\" alt=\"paris\" width=\"241\" height=\"300\" />\r\n\r\nThe Café de Paris painting is a wonderful memory of an early morning walk with my brother and my two sons in the Montparnasse section of Paris. To the left side of the river Seiene. I pictured this very unlikely moment with no one outside of the cafe but inside it is packed full of Parisians lining up for their morning espresso fix!\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-139 aligncenter\" src=\"http://insider.blaycation.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/porto-233x300.jpg\" alt=\"porto\" width=\"233\" height=\"300\" />\r\n\r\nThe Porto Painting was inspired from a multi generational family trip to Portugal. My father sitting at a table overlooking the Porto River sipping 30 year old Port will forever be burned in my memory. To me it means quality, strength and family.\r\n\r\nA big thank you to <a title=\"Megan Claire\" href=\"http://www.mappingmegan.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Megan Claire</a> who was a huge inspiration to me getting into the blogosphere. Please check out her exceptional, witty, informative travel blog here: <a title=\"Mapping Megan\" href=\"http://mappingmegan.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Mapping Megan</a>\r\n\r\nAre you an artist yourself or an art lover? What are your favourite ways are to express your inner travel memories? Tell me about it and leave a comment. If you are interested in seeing my other paintings, please let me know.\r\n\r\nIf you love experiential travel and doing it in a highly personal way, that’s what I do. I’d be happy to put together a <a title=\"Blaycation\" href=\"http://blaycation.com/bucket-list\" target=\"_blank\">Blaycation</a> for you.", "Who\'s your inner traveller?", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "whos-your-inner-traveller", "", "", "2015-09-02 00:00:33", "2015-09-02 00:00:33", "", "0", "http://localhost/blaycation/bower_components/wordpress/?post_type=blog&#038;p=66", "0", "blog", "", "0");
